				\begin{document}$$ Y{02}_{it}={\alpha}_0+{\beta}_1{CO}_{2i,t-1}+{\beta}_2{X}_{it}+{\lambda}_i+{\gamma}_t+{\varepsilon}_{it} $$\end{document}where i refers to the observation city and t refers to the observation year. Y02 is the degree of low-carbon innovation; CO2 is carbon emissions, the variable of interest. It is known that carbon emissions are difficult to be directly perceived, and people cannot react to their changes unless the information of emissions is released by the government or organizations. Thus, we used the first-order lag term of CO2 as the core explanatory variable as carbon emission data publication often has a lag period of 1 year. X are control variables, including research and development (RD), foreign direct investment (FDI), Internet users (INT), opening degree (OPEN), and gross domestic product per capita (PGDP). λi is the city-fixed effect, γt is the year-fixed effect, and εit is the error term.

To verify hypothesis 2, we regress different types of low-carbon innovation on CO2 emissions. Furthermore, to test hypothesis 3, we used the mediation models created by Baron and David (1986). The method has been widely used to test the mediation effect and its style in environmental research (Chang 2011). Equations (2)~(4) describe the three steps.
